  "enhanced_information": "For a 50-year-old man diagnosed with coronary artery disease and an LDL level of 150-165 mg/dl, the most appropriate initial therapy is statins. Statins are specifically effective in reducing LDL cholesterol, which is crucial in managing coronary artery disease. The evidence path confirming that Hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA Reductase Inhibitors (statins) treat coronary arteriosclerosis supports this choice. Other options like Gemfibrozil, Nicotinic acid, and Bile acid binding resins, although they have roles in lipid management, are less effective or have broader targets compared to the direct LDL-lowering effect of statins. Statins not only lower LDL cholesterol effectively but also improve cardiovascular outcomes, making them the optimal initial therapy in this clinical scenario."
